04710nam a22006375i 9780226429892DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20182018ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2017060714  a97802264298927 a10.7208/97802264298922doi  a(DE-B1597)550211  a(OCoLC)1057893666  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aML410.B4bW27 2018 4aML410.B4bW27 2018eb 7aMUS0000002bisacsh04a780.92223  aLP 631742rvk0(DE-625)rvk/107230:1 aWallace, Robin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHearing Beethoven :bA Story of Musical Loss and Discovery /cRobin Wallace. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (288 p.) :b14 halftones, 14 musical examples  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction: A Road Trip to Texas -- t1. Beethoven’s Deafness -- t2. 2003: A Sudden Case of Deafness -- t3. The Deaf Composer -- t4. Deafness, Vocation, Vision -- t5. The Artifacts of Deafness -- t6. Ears, Eyes, and Mind -- t7. Hearing through the Eyes -- tEpilogue. Embracing Wholeness -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWe’re all familiar with the image of a fierce and scowling Beethoven, struggling doggedly to overcome his rapidly progressing deafness. That Beethoven continued to play and compose for more than a decade after he lost his hearing is often seen as an act of superhuman heroism. But the truth is that Beethoven’s response to his deafness was entirely human. And by demystifying what he did, we can learn a great deal about Beethoven’s music. Perhaps no one is better positioned to help us do so than Robin Wallace, who not only has dedicated his life to the music of Beethoven but also has close personal experience with deafness. One day, at the age of forty-four, Wallace’s late wife, Barbara, found she couldn’t hear out of her right ear—the result of radiation administered to treat a brain tumor early in life. Three years later, she lost hearing in her left ear as well. Over the eight and a half years that remained of her life, despite receiving a cochlear implant, Barbara didn’t overcome her deafness or ever function again like a hearing person. Wallace shows here that Beethoven didn’t do those things, either. Rather than heroically overcoming his deafness, as we’re commonly led to believe, Beethoven accomplished something even more difficult and challenging: he adapted to his hearing loss and changed the way he interacted with music, revealing important aspects of its very nature in the process. Creating music became for Beethoven a visual and physical process, emanating from visual cues and from instruments that moved and vibrated. His deafness may have slowed him down, but it also led to works of unsurpassed profundity. Wallace tells the story of Beethoven’s creative life from the inside out, interweaving it with his and Barbara’s experience to reveal aspects that only living with deafness could open up. The resulting insights make Beethoven and his music more accessible, and help us see how a disability can enhance human wholeness and flourishing.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aDeafness. 7aMUSIC / General.2bisacsh  aBarbara Wallace.  aLudwig van Beethoven.  acochlear implant.  adeafness.  adepression.  adisability.  ahearing loss.  areception history.  avision.  avocation.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311068858040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226429892423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226429892.jpg  a978-3-11-068858-0  University of Chic